The Trojan horse of Europe
BERKELEY – Europe will have no choice but to bail out Greece.
Urgent funds will need to be allocated.
Urgent funds will need to be allocated with conditions.
The Greek government will make the usual promises.
This should allow the Greek government to service its debt.
The markets will calm down.
Long-term consequences will not be prohibitive, but there will be problems to come.
Some will say that the fatal error was allowing Greece to adopt the euro first.
It was already evident that the country was not ready.
Its budgetary policy was already out of control when it joined the monetary union in 2001 and its unions were already pushing for Greek wages to align with those practiced in Europe, despite lagging productivity.
But this response is too simplistic, as such signs of dysfunction are not limited to Greece.
Spain, with an unemployment rate of 20% and abyssmal budget deficits, sees Greece as an image of its own future.
And if that's not the case, the markets will take care of it.
Portugal and Italy fare somewhat better.
These countries, like Greece, must face significant budget cuts.
Like Greece, they cannot devalue their currency to encourage exports.
Like Greece, they must face a deep recession.
Like Greece, they will be tempted to seek aid.
Was the real mistake not creating the euro?
Given that I was one of the few Americans to encourage the idea of a European currency, you might ask me: are you reconsidering your initial position?
My answer is no, creating the euro was not an error, but it could well become one.
The Greek crisis shows that Europe is only halfway towards a viable monetary union.
If it does nothing, the next crisis could well render this one seem like a stroll in the park.
If it wants to complete its monetary union, Europe will have to create its own mechanism for emergency funding.
Today, members of the Union can only assist Greece by overriding regulations that prevent them from granting a loan except in the case of natural disasters or circumstances beyond the control of a country.
This exacerbates the uncertainty.
When European leaders provide assistance, public opinion and markets tend to question their honesty.
If the problems result from the Lisbon Treaty, then it needs to be amended.
Moreover, aid should not be granted solely under certain conditions, but should be accompanied by a temporary control of the national budget by a committee of "experts" appointed by the European Union.
The history shows that mere promises made by beneficiary countries are not enough.
Of course, the countries subjected to such measures will express their indignation.
But, no one forces them to accept this money.
Moral considerations?
Here is your solution.
Note that this would be a much more effective disciplinary mechanism than the defunct Stability and Growth Pact.
One could also ask the following question: how would Californians react if their state temporarily placed its budget under the control of an expert appointed specifically by President Barack Obama's administration?
In fact, it wouldn't bother them that much.
The expert would not be from California originally, but American.
Public opinion would understand that he is acting in the interest of the California state as well as in the national interest.
The fact that California sends representatives to Washington, from where these expert orders will emanate, would reassure them.
Europeans do not do this kind of thing because they primarily see themselves first and foremost as Greeks and Germans.
They do not interfere with the "sovereignty rights" of other member states.
Germany is particularly reluctant given its history during World War II, especially in Greece.
If Europe really wants to achieve its monetary union, it will have to overcome its past.
This union implies not only stronger economic ties but also closer political ties.
Those who have a solid emergency aid mechanism will actually have to account for it.
They will have to account to a strong European Parliament.
The electorate of German Chancellor Angela Merkel dislikes this kind of bailout because they know very well who will be responsible for it.
The Germans oppose any form of European political integration.
But Germany has its share of responsibility in this crisis.
She wanted an incredibly independent central bank not obligated to render accounts, but today it has adopted an excessively expansionary monetary policy, thus contributing critically to worsening the situation of the PIIGS (Portugal, Ireland, Italy, Greece, and Spain).
The huge current account surpluses of Germany further worsen their situation.
Moreover, its fiscal stimulus measures have not been sufficient to support the European economy.
Germany has benefited significantly from the creation of the euro.
It should reciprocate.
It should encourage the creation of an emergency loan facility, as well as the political integration needed to make it possible.
It must provide more fiscal support.
Is she not in the best position to push for a more responsible European Central Bank?
The Greek crisis could be the Trojan horse that will lead Europe towards a more thorough political integration.
We can only hope.
